\chapter{Bayesian Variable Selection in Neural Networks via the Horseshoe Prior}
\label{chap:horseshoe}

% -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
% 1. INTRODUCTION
% -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Deep neural networks have achieved remarkable predictive accuracy across
a wide range of scientific and applied domains, from genomics and
neuroimaging to econometrics and clinical decision-making
\missingcite{(Goodfellow, Bengio, and Courville, 2016)}.
Their expressiveness derives from the composition of many nonlinear
transformations, which allows them to approximate complex,
high-dimensional response surfaces that resist parametric description.
Yet this same expressiveness is a persistent obstacle to scientific
application: the parameters of a trained network are not interpretable
in the way that regression coefficients or smooth additive effects are,
and in particular, identifying which input variables are genuinely
relevant to the outcome---as opposed to being merely predictive
within the observed sample---is not straightforwardly addressed by
standard deep-learning methodology.

Uncertainty quantification compounds this difficulty.  A point-estimate
network, trained by minimizing a loss function via stochastic gradient
descent, provides no measure of the confidence with which any prediction
or selection is made.  For scientific inference, this is a serious
deficiency: one needs to know not only \emph{what} the network predicts,
but \emph{how certain} that prediction is, and which predictors are
driving it in a statistically meaningful sense.

Bayesian neural networks (BNNs) address both concerns by treating the
network weights as random variables and performing posterior inference
rather than point estimation.  As \citet{ghosh_model_nodate} and
\citet{ghosh_structured_2018} observe, by treating network weights as
random variables and performing posterior inference on them, BNNs can
avoid overfitting in small-data regimes, provide well-calibrated
posterior uncertainty estimates, and model a large class of stochastic
functions with heteroskedastic and multimodal noise. These properties
make BNNs a natural candidate for principled variable selection in
nonlinear settings: the posterior distribution over weights carries
information about which input features are supported by the data, and
this information can in principle be used to control the false
discovery rate.

This chapter develops a method for input variable selection in a BNN
equipped with the horseshoe prior \citep{carvalho_handling_2009,
carvalho_horseshoe_2010}.  Our approach modifies the Bayesian
compression framework of \citet{louizos_bayesian_2017} from its
original purpose---sparsifying network architectures for computational
efficiency---toward the goal of identifying which \emph{input
variables} are causally relevant to the response.  The method
combines three components that, to our knowledge, have not previously
appeared together in the literature.  First, a grouped horseshoe
prior is placed on the first-layer weights of a deep network,
inducing structured sparsity at the level of individual input
features.  Second, the posterior shrinkage factors of the horseshoe
are used as pseudo-posterior inclusion probabilities, and a
Bayesian false discovery rate (BFDR) control procedure in the spirit
of \citet{bernardo_fdr_2007} is applied to select variables at a
user-specified nominal rate.  Third, we propose a composite spectral
norm normalization to partially mitigate the identifiability problems
that arise when a global shrinkage parameter is shared across the
layers of a deep network; we demonstrate its empirical utility while
acknowledging that a complete theoretical treatment remains future
work.

We evaluate the method on synthetic data designed to capture the
nonlinear, interactive response surfaces for which neural networks
are best suited, and on the wage data from \missingcite{(Murphy and
Welch, 1990)}, which was also analyzed in Chapter~\ref{chap:semipar}
and which exhibits nonlinear age-earnings relationships of precisely
the kind that motivated this work.

