\section{Proposed Method}
\label{sec:ch3-method}

\subsection{Network Architecture and Grouped Horseshoe Prior}
\label{subsec:ch3-model}

Let $\mathbf{y} = (y_1, \ldots, y_n)^\top \in \mathbb{R}^n$
denote the observed responses and
$\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p}$ the predictor matrix,
with rows $\mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^p$.  We consider a
feedforward network with $L$ hidden layers of widths
$d_1, \ldots, d_L$ and a scalar output,
\begin{equation}
  \hat{y}_i
  = \mathbf{w}_{L+1}^\top \mathbf{z}_i^{(L)} + b_{L+1},
  \qquad
  \mathbf{z}_i^{(\ell)}
  = \sigma\!\bigl(W_\ell\,\mathbf{z}_i^{(\ell-1)} + \mathbf{b}_\ell\bigr),
  \label{eq:network}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{z}_i^{(0)} = \mathbf{x}_i$, $W_\ell \in
\mathbb{R}^{d_\ell \times d_{\ell-1}}$ and $\mathbf{b}_\ell
\in \mathbb{R}^{d_\ell}$ are the weight matrix and bias vector at
layer $\ell$, and $\sigma(\cdot)$ denotes the rectified linear
unit (ReLU) applied element-wise.  Under a Gaussian likelihood
model, $y_i \mid \hat{y}_i, \sigma_\varepsilon^2 \sim
\mathcal{N}(\hat{y}_i, \sigma_\varepsilon^2)$.

\paragraph{Grouped horseshoe on input weights.}
Variable selection is governed by the prior on the \emph{columns}
of the first-layer weight matrix $W_1$.  The $j$-th column
$\mathbf{w}_j^{(1)} = (w_{1j}^{(1)}, \ldots,
w_{d_1,j}^{(1)})^\top \in \mathbb{R}^{d_1}$ contains all
connections from input feature $j$ to the first hidden layer.
We place a grouped horseshoe prior on these columns:
\begin{equation}
  w_{kj}^{(1)} \mid \lambda_j, \tau
  \;\sim\;
  \mathcal{N}(0,\, \lambda_j^2 \tau^2),
  \quad k = 1, \ldots, d_1,\; j = 1, \ldots, p,
  \label{eq:grouped-hs}
\end{equation}
with $\lambda_j \sim \mathrm{Half\text{-}Cauchy}(0, 1)$ and
$\tau \sim \mathrm{Half\text{-}Cauchy}(0, \tau_0)$.  Because
all $d_1$ weights entering from input $j$ share the single local
scale $\lambda_j$, shrinking $\lambda_j$ toward zero effectively
severs all connections from input $j$ to the network, setting
that feature's contribution to zero regardless of the hidden-unit
structure.  The global parameter $\tau$ controls the overall
input sparsity; following \citet{piironen_hyperprior_2017},
we set $\tau_0 = p_0 / (p - p_0) \cdot n^{-1/2}$ where $p_0$ is
a prior guess at the number of active inputs.

\paragraph{Horseshoe on hidden-unit inputs.}
Placing the horseshoe on the \emph{incoming} weights of hidden
units in layers $\ell \geq 2$ additionally induces sparsity at
the level of individual neurons in layer 1.  Specifically, if the
$j$-th column of $W_2$ (the weights from neuron $j$ of the first
hidden layer to layer 2) is shrunk toward zero, then unit $j$ of
the first hidden layer is effectively inactivated and can be
pruned.  This serves two purposes: it provides a form of
``representation sparsity'' that improves interpretability of the
first hidden layer, and it mitigates the identifiability issues
discussed in Section~\ref{subsec:ch3-spectral} by constraining
the effective width of the network.  In this respect, our use of
the horseshoe in deeper layers is related to the architecture
selection approach of \citet{ghosh_structured_2018} and
\citet{ghosh_model_nodate}, though applied here as a secondary
objective subordinate to input selection rather than as the
primary goal.  Biases at all layers are given independent
$\mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_b^2)$ priors with $\sigma_b^2$ fixed.

\subsection{Variational Posterior Distributions}
\label{subsec:ch3-vardist}

We adopt a mean-field variational family following the
\emph{uncentered parameterization} of \citet{louizos_bayesian_2017}
and \citet{ghosh_structured_2018}.  Rather than directly
parameterizing the marginal distribution of $w_{kj}^{(1)}$, we
decompose it as
\begin{equation}
  w_{kj}^{(1)} = \tilde{w}_{kj}^{(1)} \cdot \lambda_j \cdot \tau,
  \label{eq:uncentered}
\end{equation}
where $\tilde{w}_{kj}^{(1)}$ is the ``uncentered'' weight, and
independently assign:
\begin{align}
  q\!\left(\tilde{w}_{kj}^{(1)}\right)
    &= \mathcal{N}\!\left(\tilde{\mu}_{kj},\, \tilde{s}_{kj}^2\right),
    \label{eq:q-weight} \\
  q(\log \lambda_j)
    &= \mathcal{N}\!\left(\mu_{\lambda_j},\, s_{\lambda_j}^2\right),
    \label{eq:q-lambda} \\
  q(\log \tau)
    &= \mathcal{N}\!\left(\mu_\tau,\, s_\tau^2\right).
    \label{eq:q-tau}
\end{align}
The uncentered parameterization improves numerical stability by
avoiding the product of potentially very small or very large
scale variables with the weights during the forward pass.  The
log-normal approximation in~\eqref{eq:q-lambda} and
\eqref{eq:q-tau} is a computationally convenient approximation
to the half-Cauchy prior; the KL divergence between these
distributions does not have a closed form but can be computed
via the auxiliary-variable representation of the half-Cauchy:
$\lambda_j^2 \mid \nu_j \sim \mathrm{InvGamma}(1/2, 1/\nu_j)$,
$\nu_j \sim \mathrm{InvGamma}(1/2, 1)$, which admits a
tractable factored KL.  Full derivations are provided in
Appendix~\ref{sec:app-ch3-elbo}.  Weights in layers $\ell \geq 2$
receive analogous uncentered parameterizations with
layer-specific local and global scales.

\subsection{Composite Spectral Norm and Identifiability}
\label{subsec:ch3-spectral}

A fundamental challenge in placing a global shrinkage parameter
$\tau$ on the first-layer weights of a deep network is that
$\tau$ is not identifiable in the strict sense: for any scalar
$c > 0$, replacing $W_1$ by $c W_1$ and $W_2$ by $c^{-1} W_2$
leaves the composed function
$W_2\,\sigma(W_1\,\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{b}_1) + \mathbf{b}_2$
unchanged (ignoring the nonlinearity, which breaks the exact
equivalence but not the approximate one near zero).  As a result,
the posterior over $\tau$ may not concentrate in a manner that
reflects the true input sparsity level; a large $\tau$ can be
compensated by globally small first-layer weights, or vice versa.

We propose normalizing the \emph{composite spectral norm} of the
network as a partial remedy.  The spectral norm $\|W_\ell\|_2$
of a weight matrix is its largest singular value, measuring
the maximum amplification of a unit-norm input by that layer.
The product $\prod_{\ell=1}^{L} \|W_\ell\|_2$ characterizes the
worst-case amplification of a signal through the entire network.
We approximately enforce
\begin{equation}
  \prod_{\ell=1}^{L} \bigl\|W_\ell\bigr\|_2 \;\approx\; 1
  \label{eq:spectral-norm}
\end{equation}
by rescaling each $W_\ell \leftarrow W_\ell / \|W_\ell\|_2^{1/L}$
at regular intervals during training.  Under this normalization,
variation in $\tau$ cannot be absorbed by a compensating change
in the spectral norms of the deeper weight matrices, giving $\tau$
a more consistent interpretation as measuring the overall scale
of input-to-output sensitivity attributable to the input layer.

We emphasize that this correction is approximate for two reasons.
First, the ReLU nonlinearity breaks the linear composition on
which the spectral norm argument relies: the true gain through
a ReLU network depends on the fraction of active units, which
varies with the input.  Second, bias parameters introduce
input-independent offsets that affect the network's output
independently of $\tau$.  A rigorous identifiability analysis
for deep BNNs with continuous shrinkage priors remains an open
theoretical problem; we demonstrate empirically in
Section~\ref{sec:ch3-experiments} that the correction improves
the stability of the inferred $\tau$ and the calibration of the
BFDR procedure.

\subsection{BFDR-Controlled Variable Selection}
\label{subsec:ch3-bfdr}

Given the fitted variational posterior, we compute the
\emph{posterior shrinkage weight} for each input $j$ as
\begin{equation}
  \hat{\kappa}_j
  = \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi}\!\left[\kappa_j\right]
  = \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi}\!\left[\frac{1}{1 + \lambda_j^2 \tau^2}\right],
  \label{eq:kappa-hat}
\end{equation}
estimated via Monte Carlo under the variational posterior.  The
quantity $1 - \hat{\kappa}_j$ serves as a pseudo-posterior
inclusion probability (pseudo-PIP) in the sense of
\citet{carvalho_handling_2009}: it approximates the probability
that input $j$ is genuinely active, as would be returned by a
spike-and-slab model.

We then apply the decision-theoretic BFDR thresholding rule of
\citet{bernardo_fdr_2007}.  Order the inputs in decreasing order
of pseudo-PIP: $1 - \hat{\kappa}_{(1)} \geq \cdots \geq
1 - \hat{\kappa}_{(p)}$.  Define the running empirical BFDR
after selecting the top $k$ inputs as
\begin{equation}
  \widehat{\mathrm{BFDR}}(k)
  = \frac{1}{k}\sum_{m=1}^{k} \hat{\kappa}_{(m)},
  \label{eq:bfdr-running}
\end{equation}
and set the threshold
\begin{equation}
  k^* = \max\!\left\{k \in \{1, \ldots, p\} :
    \widehat{\mathrm{BFDR}}(k) \leq q\right\},
  \label{eq:threshold}
\end{equation}
selecting inputs $(1), \ldots, (k^*)$ at nominal BFDR level $q$.
This is the Bayesian analogue of the Benjamini--Hochberg step-up
procedure, with pseudo-PIPs replacing $p$-values.  Theoretical
guarantees on the BFDR of this procedure in the horseshoe BNN
setting are a subject of ongoing investigation; empirical
calibration is assessed in Section~\ref{subsec:ch3-varsel}.

